    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-30T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-30T07:00:00-05:00" n="194"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d194">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.4061 Motion Pictures/230: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-30T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >October 30, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 30—8:20
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>929. Reference my despatches numbers 2250 and 2266 of October 18 and 29.<note
                        n="38" xml:id="d194fn38">Despatch No. 2266, October 29, not printed.</note>
                    As a result of the Embassy’s representations just prior to the Cabinet meeting
                    yesterday morning, the Foreign Office has now informed me that the Cabinet
                    definitely decided not to issue the projected decree law for regulation of the
                    moving picture industry.</p>
                <p>This means that the matter can only arise again if projects for legislation on
                    this subject come before Parliament when it meets.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Straus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
